    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm looking at some shipping docs for a run from Ningbo to Rotterdam. Can you explain the main differences between CIF and FOB under Incoterms 2020? Specifically, I need to know when the risk of loss actually transfers to us as the buyer.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The main difference between CIF and FOB lies in who is responsible for the goods during transit. With FOB, the buyer assumes risk and cost once the goods are loaded onto the vessel at the port of loading (Ningbo). In contrast, CIF requires the seller to cover the costs and risks of shipping the goods all the way to the named port of destination (Rotterdam). Therefore, under FOB, the risk transfers to you much sooner than it would under CIF.",
      "source": "target",
