    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. So under CIF, if something happens to the cargo while it's out on the ocean—like a container falling overboard during a storm or some kind of theft/unexplained loss—the seller is essentially the one on the hook for the insurance and the cost until it hits Rotterdam? Does the insurance coverage under CIF usually cover those kinds of maritime incidents?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, under CIF, the seller is responsible for ensuring the cargo is insured up to the destination port, which covers those maritime incidents like storms or theft. The seller must arrange and pay for the insurance, providing the buyer with proof of insurance. Although the seller manages the insurance, the extent of coverage depends on the specific insurance policy they procure, but it is intended to cover the risk up to Rotterdam. It is always wise to review the insurance certificate carefully to confirm the coverage terms.",
      "source": "target",
